title: The whole family loves this Ice maker and it has saved us money!
text:
The refrigerator ice maker cannot be used in our home because it causes flooding. My family and I use a lot of ice daily, especially me. The cost of purchasing ice at the store added up quickly - we went through two or more bags of ice each week at a cost of $2 for a 10 lb bag of ice. Easily we were spending at least $20 per month on ice. We purchased ours at Sam's Club for $99, so after about 5-6 months we have more than recovered what we would have spent on purchasing bags of ice.

For those who have complained that their units do not work, there is usually a 30-day period to ask for a replacement or refund. Looking at the overall positive reviews, it would seem that malfunctioning units are the exception rather than the rule. The item that we purchased has worked flawlessly since we purchased it, more than a year ago.

I don't know if everyone puts it to use in the same way. We use it to keep a full supply of ice in our freezer at all times. If we run low, we just fill the ice maker with water and let it do its thing. It only drops a handful of ice at a time, so if you were waiting for enough ice to fill your cup, you might get frustrated waiting. So we turn it on when our ice supply drops, and pass by occasionally to dump the ice into the freezer ice container. The ice maker will stop making ice and an indicator light will go on if the tray gets too full, or if the machine runs out of water.

I saw the reviews of other ice addicts who were very happy with this ice maker. I too am an avid ice lover... and this ice maker has been a treasured appliance in our home!

title: Great machine
text:
My small condo does not have room for a washing machine and the laundry facility for the complex is too small for the number of appartments. I ended up doing some personal items by hand in between with mixed results. A friend suggested one of those gadgets that look like an oversized blender which she used for her lingery and some other small items. It seemed to work ok but it was rather small. When I researched it on the internet I came across this little gem and ordered it instead. I liked the larger capacity and the drain made it easier to empty the water. The Panda does not have a spin cycle so I bought the table top spin dryer along with it. That was about 6 months ago and I have not made a single trip to the laudramat since then.(I will have to go there for the flannell sheets, rugs, sofa slip covers, etc) It holds about a third of a normal sized load. Since the "cycles" can be modified depending on how soiled the items are I noticed that clothes are getting visibly cleaner than with the "one wash fits all" of the commercial washing machines.I pre soak or pre wash stained items and double or triple rinse everything to remove detergent residue which dulls the colors and makes whites look gray after a while.
After some trial and error I found the best way to do my laundry is to put a large plastic foot stool inside the bathtub (use an old towel or rubber mat under it to prevent scratches) and place the washer on top of it.It should sit securely, Use the hand shower to fill it and drain the water right into the tub when done. I usually wring the clothes lightly by hand before and between rinsings but you can use the spin dryer instead. After a final spin they are just damp and ready to hang to dry. From start to finish it takes a little longer than the usual 30 minute cycle, but I don't have to sit in a basement forever waiting for a machine to become available and I can do other things around the appartment instead.
The Panda has made my life easier and has payed for itself many times over. I would buy it again in a heartbeat.

A little  late now, but Ditto for me a million times over. There is no way any human can clean this particular black glass cooktop and have it look as it should. Scrub scrub scrub. Rinse, rinse, rinse. Dry dry, dry. And then some!  ( Altho you're not supposed to, i have even resorted to a razor blade.) Others in my family have also tried cleaning this top. . A miserable experience each and every time!  I cant even boil water without the droplets  leaving a mess taking "1/2 day" ( Well , way too long and with too much effort) for it  to look clean, shiny and smear- less again.  I have had at least 12 ovens of all types throughout almost 40 years of cooking and re- locations.  I fell in love with this one because i really loved its clean, sleek looks . Two of my children also have black glass cooktops.  They assured me that keeping  the black glass top clean was a cinch.  It never dawned on me that their different brands would make such a huge difference.  Soooo, I try my best to use  the cooktop as infrequently as possible, as well as to keep the overhead lights low in that area.  What a way to live especially for someone who has always enjoyed cooking.  Now after maybe 6 months of constant agitation,  Im more than ready to throw it in the trash. In fairness tho, it cooks fine. That's as it should be of course .  Maybe i should just throw a towel over its ugly head .

title: Great dishwasher...just one risky flaw
text:
This dishwasher is one great piece of equipment. Hookup is straightforward and it really doesn't take up much space in our tiny kitchen. It works well & fits more dishes than I expected. It even holds large items, like pots & pans. Even our wok and 4-quart Crockpot fit. The large items do take up 1/4 to 1/2 of the rack space, though, so depending on your situation it may be better to wash those by hand. We've had to run dishes with really stubborn dried on food through twice, but that happens with all dishwashers. Scrape off your dishes (or soak them if needed) before loading + use a good detergent, and this baby will get everything just as clean as a full size dishwasher. I do want to note that we use the intensive cycle only, though - the manufacturer recommends using a long cycle with "tablet" detergents. I don't know how well the other cycles do yet.

As far as the problems, and the reasons for 4/5 instead of 5/5 stars:

1. The door was EXTREMELY hard to open initially, and the owner's manual is inside the dishwasher when you unpack it. It has become a bit easier to open with use, but it's still harder than it should be. This is a real danger, because the pulling force could (and has, in our case) make the dishwasher slide on the counter. Imagine what would happen if it slid off. I have been able to keep the washer in place while opening the door by bracing the bottom part below the door hinge, and I would implore anyone to BRACE THE DISHWASHER as you go to open it. I'm going to look into a non-slip pad to put under it as well for more stability...but the point remains - the door should not be this hard to open. I am disabled so I'm sure my lack of strength makes a difference, but it still seems way harder than it needs to be. The sliding is not a small issue, either.

2. The drying is so-so...most of the dishes are still kind of wet after the dishwasher is done, even after leaving the dishwasher door ajar & letting the dishes cool. We could just be unloading too soon though, and even having to dry by hand is a lot less work than dish washing by hand.

3. When we went to hook it up, we thought we were missing the faucet adapter. It's inside the faucet adapter connection on the quick connect. We spent about 10 minutes looking for it because we didn't realize it was there.

4. The dishwasher fits 11" dinner plates, but you do have to angle them a bit. They should be able to go straight up & down.

5. There is no way to get water from the faucet while the dishwasher is running. I know you could push the pressure relief valve, but I'm not sure if that's straight faucet water, or used water...and I also wouldn't want to risk lowering the water pressure even if I was sure it was clean.

Of these criticisms, only the first was a huge deal, however.

Would I buy it again? That's a resounding YES.

title: Apartment Dwellers Rejoice!
text:
So, a couple years ago we got a portable dishwasher which taught me the joys of portable appliances. So I knew these existed but with a laundry room in the corner of our building just a few doors and a flight of stairs away- we didn't really see the point in getting one.
Then I got hurt.
Even though the laundry room isn't that far, those stairs otoh were *painful* for me so, since the husband was on the road, we started talking about getting a portable washing machine. We eventually decided against it when the husband changed vocations to a tech gig where he can work from home. He's home to help me so, that kind of killed that.
Then 2020 came. And the coin shortage hit. And stuck around for several *months.* And, the conversation came up yet again.
Third time is the charm I guess cause, he caved. :D
So, these are my initial impressions and if there's anything else I encounter over the coming months, I'll post it below.

Is it easy?
For us, it worked right out of the box. With an adapter already installed on the kitchen faucet for the dishwasher, the quick release hose fit just fine already-- in fact, the only thing we "had" to buy was a dolly but that was only because we're on the second floor and it's quieter (and slightly easier) to roll in and out of position than the wheels that it already has. Were we on the ground floor, we wouldn't have bothered. So, extra points for the little wheels. They were a nice touch.

I also like the separate options- for example it can do just a rinse and spin or even just a spin if you want as well as adjust the water level. These have already proven useful for us since if you're going to overload it (and let's face facts, *everyone* overloads *any* washing machine at *some* point) you can throw it through an extra wash or an extra rinse or whatever. That's actually kinda nice.

The handholds were a thoughtful touch as well. As were the little hooks for the power cord and the drain hose. In fact, I really like the drain hose holder thing so that you can just hook it onto something (like a dish rack for example) and not have to worry about it flopping out of the sink. Water pressure is also low enough that it doesn't cause the hose to jerk around either.

So, good job on the details.

Now, how loud is it?
Obviously, the heavier the load-- the louder it's going to be but, so far? With a normal load, it's actually quieter than my dishwasher even when it spins. The only loud thing about it is the beep at the end of the cycle but, honestly? The beep isn't any louder than my microwave or even my instapot. In fact, it's the exact same beep as both my instapot and my dishwasher. Go figure. lol.
Point is that in an open concept apartment, the husband can be working his phone job in the living "room" area while the washing machine is in the kitchen and neither customers nor bosses on the phone can hear anything other than the beeps. (He's claiming that a dump truck is backing up outside if he forgets to hit the mute when it comes to an end.)

Finally, how much can it wash?
Obviously, it's portable so it's not going to handle the same amount as a full sized machine but, otoh, it's not coin operated so you can go to town and wash whenever you want. ;)
Basically? I managed to get a Full sized comforter that was a bit on the thin side through with a little babysitting. Yeah, it took a little manipulating of the load partway through and two rinses but, it went through and since that's the largest item that we have in regular use, that's okay.
Now, I would probably prefer the coin op for it because while it came out cleaner, I can't bet my life on it coming out as absolutely clean as it can possibly be but again, right now we have a coin shortage and it really needs to be washed once a month at least-- so, we're at "needs must" territory when it comes to that blanket to be honest.
Still, point *is* that it's right on that edge so if your blanket/comforter is super thick and/or Queen sized or larger, you're still gonna have to use the laundromat for that item.
To be fair though, I honestly don't see how *any* portable washing machine could handle that old comforter of mine with aplomb anyway so, I'm seriously not docking them any for that.

In short? It's wonderful. It really, really is. We don't have to "scout" whether or not there's a washer that's available anymore, we don't have to try to track down a bank that's still willing to give out quarters every couple of weeks (fewer and fewer branches seem to be doing that these days even before the shortage), and we don't have to avoid using the dish towels and cloth napkins either. Really, I foresee our paper towel usage go down as a result.

So, yeah, I love this thing! I really, really do. :D

Edit:
We are now into the first part of 2023 and it's still going strong.
Here's some more long term things that I've noticed during that time.
1) it is still *really* easy to overdo the soap!!!
I blame a lifetime of regular sized washing machines but this thing takes practically almost none.
2) it's also still kind of easy to try to overload it.
Again. I blame myself and not the machine for that.
Obviously, if you overlaod any machine too much or put in too much soap, you run the risk of getting those dreaded white streaks but a good trick for preventing that is to use the small, collapsable drying rack we bought as my guide because the perfect load seems to be just what that rack holds. Which is a really good guide, actually.
As I mentioned before though, it really isn't that big of a deal because we can easily do another load the next day. Frankly, given that by my calculations, this thing has fully paid for itself by the end of 2021 and has been actively saving us a small fortune in this last year.... I am more than okay with that. In fact, since the loads *are* so quick and easily taken care of, we have found ourselves not procrastinating on doing the laundry anymore. :D

text:
CONS:

Wash cycle: Water level only fills barely half full at highest level 5, (see photo of highest water level) so you have to manually add more water with the add water button if you want to do a full 10lb load. If you don't add more water the clothes do not move freely, and they snag on one another. You MUST manually add more water or you cannot do a full 10 lb load. Spin cycle: no spray during spin cycle so doesnt get a lot of soap out. You will need to do a second rinse. Or even a third.

The belt is starting to squeak loudly on the spin cycle after 6 month's use

Noise: The spin cycle will be heard by people living underneath you in an apartment so you'll need to set it on an appliance dolly and a rubber mat

Moveability: wheels too small so does not move easily. Get an appliance dolly

Drain: u-shaped attachment for drain hose does not fit over wider sink counters. I have to duct tape mine to the counter.

Water inlet hose: way too short.

PROS: Has good power and torque. Gets clothes very clean. Spins fast without damaging clothes. Lint trap works VERY VERY well. Great if you have pet hair!! It really gets it off!!!

Solid metal parts and motor. Not plastic.

Opinion: Quite a few upgrades needed like:

1. the water level definitely needs fixing, the tub should completely fill so clothes move freely and so I can use it as it's listed at 10lb capacity.
2. the drain hose attachment must be made wider to go over 6" wide USA counter tops,
3. Needs a spray rinse
4. Needs a longer attachment hose

Overall it's a good machine. It's better than going to the laundromat.

EDIT JANUARY 2022:
Machine still going strong! No issues after daily use for a year. A little drop of 3-n-1 oil on the spin belt and the belt stopped squeaking. A great solid machine. (Still too bad Inhave to manually adjust the water level, but the machine is so well made I just deal with it or wash less if a load.)

There is no way to attach a longer drain hose without great difficulty-the hose is glued together inside, behind the back panel. The hose is really too short.

The machine is pretty wobbly during use, I imagine due to all of the water & weight being on the left side during use. I tried this out just on my kitchen table with towels underneath to see if/how everything worked, & will definitely be looking for a sturdier stand of some kind.

title: Better than original Whynter cord!
text:
The original cord was shorter than the AC cord. This made it a bit less convenient to find places to put it in the car. So when I had to replace the original cord (It had the tip of the plug broken off) I looked for a replacement. I saw this, and while rather expensive I decided to order it. The new cord is a heavier gauge wire than the original, which is a good safety feature that keeps the wire from overheating and also wastes less of our battery from resistance. It is MUCH easier to find a good place to put the cooler when you have ten feet of cord! The only small minus is that unlike the old cord that has a straight plug, this has a 90 degree right angle. So even if the 12v port is on the left you still have it going off to the right before you bend it over. On a short cord this would make it harder to reach the port if it's on the wrong side. But with this much length it just looks a bit funny...

So, while I wish it wasn't so expensive I think it's worth it. I wish Whynter had an option of buying the cooler with it instead of the short cord!

title: I'd give it 5 stars if it had a separate rinse or spin cycle
text:
I had a Haier 1.0gal washing machine, purchased used, that lasted 3 years of abuse before the motor finally failed. I managed to score one of the Whirlpool portable washers for dirt cheap. It's about twice the size and weight of the Haier, and is about the same size as my portable dishwasher. It's only a little louder than the Haier even though the motor is so much better, but not much and I really only hear it during the spin cycle in my small duplex. There's a loud 'click' when the cycle finishes, no beeps or anything, which I rather like.

Protip: It's a high efficiency unit, and low or no suds detergent should be used. Regular laundry soap will gunk up everything in side rather quickly. Also, Whirlpool sells a stacking unit for this, so if you have the Whirlpool compact electric dryer, it can be mounted above this washer if space is a premium, but you lose mobility because it's awkward to wheel around like that.

I've had no problem with the spin or pump, mine works fine on all cycles. I love everything about this machine. The little cup that holds the powdered detergent is set up so the incoming water goes right through it, dissolving it before it gets onto the laundry, so no more blotchy messes.

My only 'druther' is that I wish it had a dedicated rinse or spin cycle. While you can interrupt a regular cycle by lifting the lid (because it won't operate at all if the lid is up) it would just be nice if there was a dedicated cycle for it for those times when I'm washing a super absorbent load, like sweaters, so I could do an additional rinse to be sure all the soap is out.

title: Temperamental fridge with too many flaws for the price
text:
I have had this fridge for about four years (the same family of appliances, E522B), and the verdict is that its looks, efficient use of space and small footprint (which is a must if you have limited space) are almost outweighed by flaws that are unforgivable for this price range. First, the

PROs:
Small footprint
Great looks, clean, classy, angular
Efficient use of space
Lots of nifty features and nice touches you'd expect for the price
Acceptably energy-efficient

BUT here come the

CONS:
Dents easily - out of nowhere, it's enough for someone to walk by it
It's mechanically unreliable - the ice tray quit working years ago, the screen is erratic and either works, works partially or not at all, some compartment doors snapped out within the first six months, etc.
It's expensive to fix, even a service diagnostic call will cost you a bundle
Fisher & Paykel customer service is horrid

Bottom line: if you can find a similar size fridge from someone else, buy it - you'll save a lot of money, headaches and frustration. It is a shame really because I really do love my fridge - but it's been a thorn in my side for most of the time I've owned it,
